Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: My intuition stems from the observation that while Papers 1–3 explore variations of information density in discourse, they largely treat discourse structure and information flow as static or linearly evolving phenomena. Paper 1 introduces the Structured Context Hypothesis, linking hierarchical discourse to surprisal patterns—yet it does not model how this hierarchy dynamically evolves over time or how transitions between discourse units affect predictability. Paper 2 focuses on local syntactic choices influenced by prior discourse, and Paper 3 examines contextual units in dialogues but stops short of modeling the multi-scale temporal dynamics inherent in complex texts. I propose a novel integration of Rhetorical Structure Theory (RST) with time-series modeling of information density, treating discourse not just as a tree but as a dynamic system where structural depth modulates the predictability of future information load. This idea differs fundamentally by introducing *temporal dependency* into RST-aware models: instead of using discourse hierarchy only as static features, we model how movement through the RST tree—up, down, or across nuclei and satellites—affects the trajectory of information density. By combining RST parsing with sequence modeling (e.g., transformers or state-space models), we can capture how deep rhetorical structures (e.g., elaboration chains, contrastive branches) create rhythmic patterns in information delivery. The novelty lies in framing discourse as a *predictive dynamical system*, where both structural position and rhetorical function jointly regulate expected surprisal. This moves beyond UID as a smoothing principle and beyond static feature-based models, offering a mechanistic account of why certain narrative arcs feel "dense" or "predictable." It also opens new applications in text generation, summarization, and readability optimization.

