  "Idea": "This research introduces 'Reasoning as Discourse Planning' (RDP), a novel generative framework that reinterprets Rhetorical Structure Theory (RST) not as a descriptive annotation scheme but as the output of an internal planning process executed by a reasoning agent managing information flow for optimal comprehension. While prior work correlates static RST parses with observed information density, this project investigates whether such structures naturally emerge when a language model plans utterances through a goal-directed, modular reasoning process that anticipates future cognitive load. We hypothesize that human-like discourse hierarchies arise when an agent balances two objectives: maximizing communicative effectiveness (e.g., clarity, completeness) and minimizing future unpredictability (i.e., smoothing surprisal). To test this, we develop a modular agent architecture inspired by dual-process theory: a fast, context-encoding representation module processes incoming discourse state, while a slower, deliberative reasoning module—composed of specialized submodules for rhetorical functions (e.g., elaboration, contrast, backgrounding)—dynamically constructs the next discourse unit. Crucially, the agent uses a world model (implemented via a latent state predictor) to simulate multiple rollout paths of potential rhetorical choices, estimating their impact on future information density using a learned surprisal forecaster. At each step, the agent selects actions (rhetorical relations and content) via Monte Carlo Tree Search (MCTS), guided by a reward function combining immediate coherence, long-term predictability, and structural balance (e.g., nucleus-satellite equilibrium). Over time, this process generates RST-like trees endogenously, without supervision. We then evaluate whether these self-generated structures replicate empirical properties of natural discourse (e.g., right-branching bias, nucleus dominance, periodicity in information flow). By comparing generated vs. annotated RST trees (from RST-DT), we assess the extent to which human discourse organization can be explained as the solution to a planning problem under cognitive constraints. A key contribution is the introduction of 'Planning Emergence Score' (PES), which quantifies structural similarity between generated and human-annotated trees while controlling for surface content. This framework enables us to move beyond correlation to causal explanation: instead of asking 'does structure affect predictability?', we ask 'does predictability pressure give rise to structure?'. Applications include generating pedagogical texts with optimized cognitive pacing, building dialogue systems that adapt rhetoric in real-time, and reverse-engineering implicit principles of effective communication.",
