  "Idea": "This research proposes a novel framework that integrates Rhetorical Structure Theory (RST) with temporal modeling of information density to investigate how the hierarchical organization of discourse units governs the predictability of information fluctuations over time. While the Uniform Information Density (UID) hypothesis suggests speakers aim for even distribution of information, empirical data show systematic deviations that correlate with discourse structure. Building on the Structured Context Hypothesis (Paper 1), this work advances the field by modeling discourse not as a static hierarchy but as a dynamic process in which transitions between discourse roles (e.g., nucleus-satellite relations) modulate future information load. Specifically, we hypothesize that the depth, branching complexity, and rhetorical function of discourse units in an RST parse tree influence the temporal autocorrelation and predictability of surprisal contours. For instance, sequences involving recursive elaboration may exhibit lower-frequency oscillations in information density, whereas rapid shifts between contrasting units (e.g., concession, antithesis) may induce high-frequency unpredictability. We will operationalize this by aligning RST-parsed documents (from corpora like the RST-DT) with fine-grained surprisal estimates derived from large language models (LLMs), then apply time-series forecasting models (e.g., Transformers with structural attention masks, or continuous-time state-space models) to predict future surprisal based on both local linguistic context and global RST path history. Crucially, our model will incorporate 'structural embeddings' that encode the current position in the RST tree (e.g., depth, distance to root, sibling count), enabling the system to learn how structural dynamics shape information predictability. We further introduce a metric—'Structural Predictability Gain' (SPG)—that quantifies how much RST-informed models outperform context-only baselines in forecasting surprisal trajectories. This approach enables us to answer not just whether structure predicts information density, but how the *evolution* of structure shapes the *temporal rhythm* of comprehension difficulty. The implications are broad: from improving educational text design by pacing rhetorical complexity, to enhancing AI-generated narratives with cognitively plausible information flow, and refining dialogue systems to manage user cognitive load dynamically.",
